WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.080
[Music]

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:13.520
Good day. I'm Norman Wildberger, and this is a new&nbsp;
series that's going to explore the foundations of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.520 --> 00:00:22.000
modern mathematics in a new and better way. I'm&nbsp;
a research mathematician at the University of New&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:30.480
South Wales in Sydney, Australia. I'm also the&nbsp;
discoverer of rational trigonometry. The aims of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:39.240
this series are primarily three: I want to expose&nbsp;
some of the weaknesses that currently exist in set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.240 --> 00:00:48.840
theory, in analysis, and in various other related&nbsp;
areas of mathematics, including geometry. I want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:59.040
to also lay a new foundation for mathematics, a&nbsp;
framework which makes sense, which doesn't rely on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:07.400
authority, doesn't rely on various unsubstantiated&nbsp;
axiomatic systems, one that anyone can understand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:15.080
who wants to follow from the beginning. The third&nbsp;
aim is I want to provide a resource for teachers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:15.080 --> 00:01:21.520
for public school teachers, and for high school&nbsp;
teachers. I want to explain the subject in a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:28.520
way that people developing curriculum can have a&nbsp;
basis for making rational decisions about what to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.520 --> 00:01:35.000
include and what not to include. Now, this will&nbsp;
not be a course in mathematics. I'm interested&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.200
in laying the foundations but not on building&nbsp;
elaborate theories. So I'm going to go around,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:45.600
and we're going to look at various topics and ask&nbsp;
ourselves what are really the essential notions&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:53.560
here. What are the main definitions? How do they&nbsp;
fit into place correctly? When mathematics is done&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.560 --> 00:02:01.720
right, all the blocks do fit together really well.&nbsp;
It's not artificial; things really do work out,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:07.480
and this is going to be the test for us, that&nbsp;
we're really doing things in the right way. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.480 --> 00:02:12.240
our main principles that we'll follow are that&nbsp;
we're going to start right from the beginning.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:17.920
We're not going to assume that you already have&nbsp;
a PhD in set theory and logic. We're not going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:24.480
assume a lot of sophistication, a lot of jargon.&nbsp;
We're going to start from the beginning. The first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.480 --> 00:02:30.320
steps are usually the most important ones in any&nbsp;
journey, and it's especially true when developing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.320 --> 00:02:38.360
mathematics. You have to start from the beginning,&nbsp;
and you have to start in a simple way. So we are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:38.360 --> 00:02:44.640
going to keep things simple and natural. We're&nbsp;
going to try to connect with the real world at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:52.440
all times, and finally, we're going to keep an&nbsp;
open mind. We're not going to just accept the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.440 --> 00:02:59.240
usual orthodoxy because people tell us, and we're&nbsp;
also going to be prepared that we don't have the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:07.080
final say, that we may be prepared to revisit what&nbsp;
we have already done in later videos and come back&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.080 --> 00:03:14.120
and think about things in slightly different ways&nbsp;
if necessary. So how are we going to start? We're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:14.120 --> 00:03:21.800
going to start with the most important subject&nbsp;
in mathematics. The most important objects in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:29.000
mathematics, the most important mathematical&nbsp;
objects, are the natural numbers: 1, 2, 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:35.040
4, and so on. These have obviously been&nbsp;
around for hundreds of thousands of years,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.040 --> 00:03:41.360
and as we develop them from first principles,&nbsp;
let's not get too sophisticated. The starting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:41.360 --> 00:03:49.800
point is an empty page, nothing. This is&nbsp;
how we start mathematics. We start with

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:58.680
nothing. Now we want to introduce&nbsp;
something. There is our symbol for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:58.680 --> 00:04:05.640
something. It represents a single&nbsp;
entity. I'm going to call it

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:14.760
one. So we have had nothing before. Now we have&nbsp;
a single entity which we're calling one. It's a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.760 --> 00:04:20.480
stroke on the paper. We could also represent it&nbsp;
with a dot or a circle or something else, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:29.720
let's agree it's a little vertical stroke. Then&nbsp;
the next idea is the idea of adding one to itself.

00:04:31.240 --> 00:04:39.840
One and another one, that makes&nbsp;
a number which we'll call two,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:45.920
and then we can iterate. We can keep on adding&nbsp;
one to what we've already got to get a sequence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:45.920 --> 00:05:00.080
of objects which we'll call at this point 1,&nbsp;
1, 1, 1, 1, and so on, whose names will be

00:05:00.080 --> 00:05:03.000
3,

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:14.120
4, 5, and so on. So we do not assume yet&nbsp;
the Arabic Hindu notational system that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.120 --> 00:05:19.200
we're all used to because that's a much&nbsp;
more sophisticated idea. So currently,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:25.560
what a natural number is is just a string&nbsp;
of ones. So let's write that down as a main

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:30.560
definition. Natural

00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:39.800
number is a

00:05:39.800 --> 00:05:46.080
string of

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:56.240
ones. Mathematical objects are all going&nbsp;
to be based on natural numbers. These are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.240 --> 00:05:59.840
our first mathematical objects, and&nbsp;
it turns out that everything else&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:59.840 --> 00:06:08.040
that we do will ultimately be based on&nbsp;
natural numbers. So a few observations:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:16.440
the natural numbers form a sequence. They are&nbsp;
naturally ordered. To every natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:23.120
we can associate the next one, which we might&nbsp;
call the successor. So we can say that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:32.440
successor of one is one or two. The successor of&nbsp;
two is three, and so on. So this is a notion of

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:42.320
successor. It's our first example of a&nbsp;
mathematical operation. We take a number;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:42.320 --> 00:06:48.840
its successor is another number. So&nbsp;
my daughter loves Littlest Pet Shops,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:57.200
and there are dozens of these little things lying&nbsp;
around our house. And so here are a bunch of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:07.320
Littlest Pet Shops. Suppose we want to count how&nbsp;
many there are. Well, what we do is first one we

00:07:07.320 --> 00:07:16.760
make a stroke, for the next&nbsp;
one we make a stroke, next

00:07:16.760 --> 00:07:29.320
one stroke, next one a stroke,&nbsp;
and the next one another stroke,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.320 --> 00:07:35.360
and then we say that the number of&nbsp;
Littlest Pet Shops was 1, 1, 1, 1, 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.360 --> 00:07:43.080
which we also call five. So we have the natural&nbsp;
numbers, we have the natural successor function.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:43.080 --> 00:07:48.280
The other important concept that's really&nbsp;
elementary is the notion of relative size:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:48.280 --> 00:08:00.960
which one is bigger, which one is smaller. So if&nbsp;
we have two numbers, say that one and that one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:00.960 --> 00:08:06.320
then to compare those two numbers, in other words,&nbsp;
to find out which one comes first in the sequence,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:18.080
what we do is we think about pairing the ones&nbsp;
in each sequence. You see we've paired up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:18.080 --> 00:08:23.080
the elements, the ones in the first string,&nbsp;
with some of the ones in the second string,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:23.080 --> 00:08:28.840
and we have some left over. This tells us that the&nbsp;
second one is larger than the first number. So we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:28.840 --> 00:08:37.040
have a notion of bigger than. Now let's introduce&nbsp;
a little bit of abstract notation. Okay, let's

00:08:37.040 --> 00:08:50.280
represent a natural number, which&nbsp;
we'll just call a number, by a letter,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.280 --> 00:09:04.000
so it's a general thing. For example, n or m.&nbsp;
So now we can say that n equals m. By that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:14.800
mean that the ones in n can be paired up with the&nbsp;
ones in m. That's the notion of equality when two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:22.720
numbers are the same. And we also have a notion&nbsp;
of inequality. We say that n is less than m,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:34.360
which means that n comes before m in the sequence&nbsp;
of natural numbers. Now that we have what the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:40.080
natural numbers are, the next step is to think&nbsp;
about arithmetical operations on natural numbers:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:44.360
addition, multiplication, subtraction, and&nbsp;
division. That's what we're going to do with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:44.360 --> 00:09:54.364
our next video. I hope you'll join me. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wer, thanks for [Music] listening.

